    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-16T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-16T16:00:00-05:00" n="278"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d278">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/15270: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stettinius</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-16T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 16, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>238. 1. Department is concerned over the steady deterioration of
                    Kuomintang–Communist relations as revealed by Embassy’s comprehensive and timely
                    reports on the subject.</p>
                <p>2. Department is therefore giving serious consideration to the advisability of
                    urging the Generalissimo to agree to the dispatch of a small group of American
                    military and other observers to Communist controlled territory. We understand
                    that the War Department is also giving consideration to this matter. It is felt
                    that among other <pb facs="0351" n="337" xml:id="pg_337"/> reasons such a move
                    is desirable from the point of view of our present and future military
                    operations in China. While it would probably be advisable that the mission be of
                    a military character it would seem desirable that it include one or more Foreign
                    Service officers trained as political observers.</p>
                <p>3. Department would appreciate receiving an expression of the Embassy’s views in
                    regard to the suggested action set forth in paragraph 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
